<subSubSection id="C31665703237FFDD83E9FD482822FBF2" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BB336FB3237FFDD83E9FD482D4DFD6F" blockId="8.[151,1437,655,1257]" box="[151,358,655,681]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<heading id="D0FB81973237FFDD83E9FD482D4DFD6F" box="[151,358,655,681]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" reason="5">
<taxonomicName id="4C0C4D783237FFDD83E9FD482D4DFD6F" baseAuthorityName="Langguth &amp; Bonvincino" baseAuthorityYear="2002" box="[151,358,655,681]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Cerradomys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scotti">
<emphasis id="B978EAE93237FFDD83E9FD482D4DFD6F" box="[151,358,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Cerradomys scotti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB336FB3237FFDD83B9FD742822FBF2" blockId="8.[151,1437,655,1257]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Karyotype: 2n = 58 and FN = 70. Autosomal complement: seven small metacentric and submetacentric pairs, and 21 acrocentric pairs large to small decreasing in size. Sex chromosomes: X chromosome presented three different morphologies, a large submetacentric (Xa), a large subtelocentric (Xb), and a large subtelocentric shorter than Xb (Xc); Y chromosome presented three different morphologies, a medium submetacentric (Ya), a medium subtelocentric (Yb), and a medium acrocentric (Yc). C-banding metaphases exhibited blocks of constitutive heterochromatin on the pericentromeric region of all autosomes. The X chromosomes presented their short arms and centromeric regions heterochromatic, besides two interstitial bands on its long arms. The three 
<typeStatus id="54B788593237FFDD87F4FC4C28EEFC62" box="[1162,1221,907,933]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">types</typeStatus>
of Y chromosomes presented their long arms almost entirely heterochromatic. G- and R-banding were also performed. Multiple NORs, varying from three to eleven, were localized on the short arms of acrocentric autosomes (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3237FFDD87D8FC142CF4FBD6" author="Svartman, M. &amp; Almeida, E. J. C." pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="313 - 324" refId="ref74361" refString="Svartman, M. &amp; Almeida, E. J. C. (1992 a) Sex chromosomes polymorphisms in Oryzomys aff. subflavus (Cricetidae, Rodentia) from central Brazil. Caryologia, 45 (3 - 4), 313 - 324. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00087114.1992.10797234" type="journal article" year="1992">Svartman &amp; Almeida 1992a</bibRefCitation>
, pp. 317, 
<figureCitation id="13372A7E3237FFDD8232FC302DA7FBD6" box="[332,396,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1976,2000]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,1069,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-342@4.[159,1429,1062,1950]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Collection localities of Oryzomyini species analyzed in this work. (1) Claúdia, Mato Grosso state; (2) and (3) Rio Japurá, Amazonas state; (4) and (5) Rio Içá, Amazonas state." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423617" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423617/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). FISH with telomeric sequences revealed signals exclusively at the ends of all chromosome arms and no interstitial signals were observed (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3237FFDD81DBFBDC2FD5FBF2" author="Andrades-Miranda, J. &amp; Zanchin, N. I. T. &amp; Oliveira, L. F. B. &amp; Langguth, A. R. &amp; Mattevi, M. S." box="[677,1022,1051,1077]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="11 - 16" refId="ref63860" refString="Andrades-Miranda, J., Zanchin, N. I. T., Oliveira, L. F. B., Langguth, A. R. &amp; Mattevi, M. S. (2002) (T 2 AG 3) n telomeric sequence hybridization indicating centric fusion rearrangements in the karyotype of the rodent Oryzomys subflavus. Genetica, 114, 11 - 16. https: // doi. org / 10.1023 / A: 1014645731798" type="journal article" year="2002">
Andrades-Miranda 
<emphasis id="B978EAE93237FFDD80FCFBDC2F98FBF2" box="[898,947,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">et al</emphasis>
. 2002
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31665703237FFDD83B9FBF82D2EFB2E" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB336FB3237FFDD83B9FBF82D2EFB2E" blockId="8.[151,1437,655,1257]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
The same diploid number was reported by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3237FFDD81D5FBF82F9FFB9E" author="Bonvicino, C. R. &amp; Otazu, I. B. &amp; Borodin, P. M." box="[683,948,1087,1113]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="327 - 332" refId="ref64821" refString="Bonvicino, C. R., Otazu, I. B. &amp; Borodin, P. M. (1999) Chromosome variation in Oryzomys subflavus species group (Sigmodontinae, Rodentia) and its taxonomic implication. Cytologia, 64, 327 - 332. https: // doi. org / 10.1508 / cytologia. 64.327" type="journal article" year="1999">
Bonvicino 
<emphasis id="B978EAE93237FFDD8059FBF82F72FB9E" box="[807,857,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">et al</emphasis>
. (1999)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3237FFDD80BEFBF8293CFB9E" author="Langguth, A. &amp; Bonvicino, C. R." box="[960,1303,1087,1113]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="285 - 294" refId="ref68527" refString="Langguth, A. &amp; Bonvicino, C. R. (2002) The Oryzomys subflavus species group, with description of two new species (Rodentia, Muridae, Sigmodontinae). Arquivos do Museu Nacional, 60 (4), 285 - 294." type="journal article" year="2002">Langguth &amp; Bonvicino (2002)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3237FFDD8630FBF82D75FBBA" author="Bonvicino, C. R. &amp; Lemos, B. &amp; Weksler, M." pageId="8" pageNumber="9" pagination="395 - 406" refId="ref65016" refString="Bonvicino, C. R., Lemos, B. &amp; Weksler, M. (2005) Small mammals of Chapada dos Veadeiros National Park (cerrado of central Brazil): ecologic, karyologic, and taxonomic considerations. Brazilian Journal of Biology, 65 (3), 395 - 406. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 1519 - 69842005000300004" type="journal article" year="2005">
Bonvicino 
<emphasis id="B978EAE93237FFDD83B1FBA42D2AFBBA" box="[207,257,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">et al</emphasis>
. (2005)
</bibRefCitation>
. These authors reported a different fundamental number of 72 due to a presence of one medium subtelocentric pair instead of a medium acrocentric one, and two males carrying one additional B chromosome. These variation in fundamental number occurs sympatrically on specimens collected in 
<collectingRegion id="49C8F8193237FFDD871BFB6C2882FB02" box="[1125,1193,1195,1221]" country="Brazil" name="Goias" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Goiás</collectingRegion>
, state of 
<collectingCountry id="F31B766B3237FFDD8675FB6C2964FB02" box="[1291,1359,1195,1221]" name="Brazil" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<tableCitation id="C68E03403237FFDD8623FB6C2C8CFB2E" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="9.[151,235,587,612]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="TABLE 2. Karyotype data of genus Cerradomys. Species, diploid (2n) and fundamental (FN) numbers, collection localities, geographic coordinates and reference." pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Table 2</tableCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13372A7E3237FFDD83CDFB082CD3FB2E" box="[179,248,1231,1257]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1191,1215]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,281,1162]" captionTargetId="figure-69@7.[151,1436,273,1168]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distribution of diploid and fundamental number of karyotyped specimens of genus Cerradomys. (□) C. akroai; (■) C. goytaca; (ê) C. langguthi; (r) C. maracajuensis; (▲) C. marinhus; (○) C. scotti; (☆) C. subflavus; (l) C. vivoi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423619/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
